artists.biography: Correctly tagged as Kyle Dixon & Michael Stein, they are members of the American synth band S U R V I V E and composers of the soundtrack to Netflix's hit series "Stranger Things". Just as its story goes deep referencing the classics of VHS era science fiction and horror movies, Dixon and Stein's music is hugely inspired by the likes of John Carpenter and Tangerine Dream, the masters of tension and synth soundscapes. While indebted to the classics, they've still managed to create instantly recognizable classic themes, making the series even more mysterious and memorable. Read more on Last.fm. apple_music.editorial_notes: No locked curiosity-door, here. Just lush, synth-soaked soundscapes that helped set the tone for one of TV’s buzziest ever first seasons. Obviously, Dixon and Stein—who moonlight as Austin Korg-maestros S U R V I V E and supplied music for the soundtrack to revivalist splatterfest The Guest—lovingly ransack ‘80s ambience. But there are thrilling changes in pace, as evidenced by the drum stabs on the fittingly haunting “Lights Out”.

editorialNotes.short: Immaculate moody electronica. Take your own trip to the "Upside-Down”.
